t: Psalm 66
To the chief Musician, A Song or Psalm.
Make*p a joyful noise unto God, all ye lands:
Sing*p forth the honour of his name: make his praise glorious.
Say*p unto God, How terrible art thou in thy works! through the greatness of thy power shall thine enemies submit themselves unto thee.
All*p the earth shall worship thee, and shall sing unto thee; they shall sing to thy name. Selah.
Come*p and see the works of God: he is terrible in his doing toward the children of men.
He*p turned the sea into dry land: they went through the flood on foot: there did we rejoice in him.
He*p ruleth by his power for ever; his eyes behold the nations: let not the rebellious exalt themselves. Selah.
O*p bless our God, ye people, and make the voice of his praise to be heard:
Which*p holdeth our soul in life, and suffereth not our feet to be moved.
For*p thou, O God, hast proved us: thou hast tried us, as silver is tried.
Thou*p broughtest us into the net; thou laidst affliction upon our loins.
Thou*p hast caused men to ride over our heads; we went through fire and through water: but thou broughtest us out into a wealthy place.
I*p will go into thy house with burnt offerings: I will pay thee my vows,
Which*p my lips have uttered, and my mouth hath spoken, when I was in trouble.
I*p will offer unto thee burnt sacrifices of fatlings, with the incense of rams; I will offer bullocks with goats. Selah.
Come*p and hear, all ye that fear God, and I will declare what he hath done for my soul.
I*p cried unto him with my mouth, and he was extolled with my tongue.
If*p I regard iniquity in my heart, the Lord will not hear me:
But*p verily God hath heard me; he hath attended to the voice of my prayer.
Blessed*p be God, which hath not turned away my prayer, nor his mercy from me.
